# XO-catch

XO-catch is a local multiplayer board game implemented in C with:

- a TCP server (`server.c`) that owns game state and persistence
- a Raylib client (`client.c`) for UI/input
- shared game rules in `game_logic.c`

The transport protocol is newline-delimited JSON (`one JSON object per line`).

## What Is Implemented

### Server

- Creates games with board sizes from `3` to `25`
- Assigns first player as `X`, second player as `O`, additional joiners as `SPECTATOR`
- Supports reconnect with player token (`JOIN_GAME` with `token`)
- Enforces token auth and turn order for `MOVE`
- Validates internal move application and rejects failed logic calls without mutating game state
- Supports polling via `GET_STATE`
- Supports `QUIT_GAME` (finishes game with `finish_reason="quit"`)
- Tracks per-player disconnect flags (`x_disconnected`, `o_disconnected`)
- Persists each game to `./data/game_<id>.json`
- Lazy-loads games from disk when not yet loaded in memory
- Rejects `JOIN_GAME` and `MOVE` for finished games (`GET_STATE` still allowed)

### Client

- Menu UI: create game, join game by numeric id, exit application.
- Gameplay UI: board rendering, current turn/status text, spectator banner, waiting banner, and finished overlay with winner/reason.
- Controls: Arrow keys or `WASD` to move; `ESC` quits (players send `QUIT_GAME`) or returns to menu (spectators).
- Network behavior: periodic `GET_STATE` polling and reconnect/reclaim through `JOIN_GAME` with token after connection loss.

### Game Rules Implemented

For each move direction (`UP`, `DOWN`, `LEFT`, `RIGHT`):

1. Clone along direction (jumping over opponent cells, landing on first empty cell).
2. Remove opponent groups with no liberties (captured pieces vanish).
3. Remove mover groups with no liberties (suicide removal).
4. Switch active player.
5. Evaluate end conditions.

End conditions currently implemented:

- player elimination
- full board (winner by piece count, or draw on tie)
- both-zero fallback draw (`finish_reason="both_zero"`)
- quit (`finish_reason="quit"`)

## Build

Server:

```bash
gcc -std=c11 -Wall -Wextra -O2 -o server server.c game_logic.c -lcjson
```

If your system has `libcjson.so.1` but no `libcjson.so` linker symlink:

```bash
gcc -std=c11 -Wall -Wextra -O2 -o server server.c game_logic.c \
  -L/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu -Wl,-rpath,/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu -Wl,-l:libcjson.so.1
```

Client:

```bash
gcc -std=c11 -Wall -Wextra -O2 -o client client.c $(pkg-config --cflags --libs raylib) -lcjson
```

If your system has `libcjson.so.1` but no `libcjson.so` linker symlink:

```bash
gcc -std=c11 -Wall -Wextra -O2 -o client client.c $(pkg-config --cflags --libs raylib) \
  -L/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu -Wl,-rpath,/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu -Wl,-l:libcjson.so.1
```

If Raylib is installed as a static library and `pkg-config --libs raylib` is not enough:

```bash
gcc -std=c11 -Wall -Wextra -O2 -o client client.c -I/usr/local/include -L/usr/local/lib -lraylib \
  -L/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu -Wl,-rpath,/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu -Wl,-l:libcjson.so.1 \
  -lm -lpthread -ldl -lrt -lX11 -lGL -lXrandr -lXi -lXcursor -lXinerama
```

## Run

Default local setup:

```bash
./server
./client
```

Optional host/port overrides:

```bash
./server [bind_ip] [port]
./client [host] [port]
```

Defaults are `127.0.0.1:8080`.

Examples:

```bash
./server 127.0.0.1 8080     # local-only (default behavior)
./server 0.0.0.0 8080       # LAN-accessible on all interfaces
./server 192.168.1.50 8080  # bind to one specific LAN interface
./client 127.0.0.1 8080
./client 192.168.1.50 8080  # connect over LAN
```

## Protocol and State

Supported commands:

- `NEW_GAME`
- `JOIN_GAME`
- `MOVE`
- `GET_STATE`
- `QUIT_GAME`

The server returns full state snapshots in responses. The canonical protocol and field definitions are documented in `PROTOCOL.md`.

## Persistence

- Game files are stored in `./data/`.
- Writes are performed via temp-file + rename.
- State includes board, active player, tokens, disconnect flags, game status, winner/reason, and timestamps.

## Testing

`integration_test.sh` runs protocol-level server integration checks for:

- validation and role assignment
- move auth and turn enforcement
- deterministic capture/suicide scenario
- quit and finished-game restrictions
- lazy-load from disk

It does not automate Raylib UI behavior.
